description:
Create a GitLab CI pipeline that uses the docker:24 Docker image with the docker:24-dind service and defines the stages build, test, security, review and production. In the build stage add a job called build_image that runs the following script: 
- registry_login (calls docker login -u $CI_REGISTRY_USER -p $CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD $CI_REGISTRY)
- if a Dockerfile exists, execute docker build --build-arg HTTP_PROXY="$HTTP_PROXY" --build-arg http_proxy="$http_proxy" --build-arg HTTPS_PROXY="$HTTPS_PROXY" --build-arg https_proxy="$https_proxy" --build-arg FTP_PROXY="$FTP_PROXY" --build-arg ftp_proxy="$ftp_proxy" --build-arg NO_PROXY="$NO_PROXY" --build-arg no_proxy="$no_proxy" -t "$CI_APPLICATION_REPOSITORY:$CI_APPLICATION_TAG" .; else run the Herokuish build using docker run -i -e BUILDPACK_URL -e HTTP_PROXY -e http_proxy -e HTTPS_PROXY -e https_proxy -e FTP_PROXY -e ftp_proxy -e NO_PROXY -e no_proxy gliderlabs/herokuish /bin/herokuish buildpack build; then docker tag the resulting image.
- docker push "$CI_APPLICATION_REPOSITORY:$CI_APPLICATION_TAG".
The job runs on all branches (no rules restriction).
In the test stage add a job called test that runs: 
- setup_test_db (sets DATABASE_URL to a local or Kubernetes postgres host)
- install_dependencies (apk add openssl curl tar gzip bash ca-certificates git; install helm and kubectl)
- your project’s test command, e.g., pip install -r requirements.txt && pytest --junitxml=report.xml
- store report.xml as a JUnit artifact.
In the security stage add five jobs: container_scanning, sast, dependency_scanning, code_quality and license_management. Each job runs its respective function defined in .auto_devops: 
- container_scanning runs docker login, starts a clair DB container, starts the clair scanner, downloads clair-scanner binary, waits for the daemon, then runs ./clair-scanner … producing gl-container-scanning-report.json;
- sast runs docker run with the GitLab SAST image (registry.gitlab.com/gitlab-org/security-products/sast:$SP_VERSION) mounting the code and Docker socket;
- dependency_scanning runs docker run with the dependency‑scanning image (registry.gitlab.com/gitlab-org/security-products/dependency-scanning:$SP_VERSION);
- code_quality runs docker run with the code‑quality image (registry.gitlab.com/gitlab-org/security-products/codequality:$SP_VERSION);
- license_management runs /run.sh analyze .
All security jobs upload their JSON reports as artifacts and are triggered only for merge‑request pipelines (rules: if $CI_MERGE_REQUEST_ID).
In the review stage add a job called review_deploy that runs: 
- check_kube_domain (fails if AUTO_DEVOPS_DOMAIN is not set);
- ensure_namespace (creates $KUBE_NAMESPACE if missing);
- download_chart (helm init, add gitlab repo, fetch and unpack the auto‑devops chart);
- deploy review (calls deploy function with track=review, calculates replicas via get_replicas, runs helm upgrade --install with image repository $CI_APPLICATION_REPOSITORY and tag $CI_APPLICATION_TAG, sets service.enabled, replicaCount, database URL, etc.);
- scale down old releases if needed.
The job runs on all branches except protected branches (rules: if $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH != "main").
In the production stage add a job called production_deploy that runs the same deploy function but with track=stable and then runs a cleanup step that calls scale to adjust replica counts; it only runs on the main branch and on tags (rules: if $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main" or $CI_COMMIT_TAG).
All jobs use the same docker:24 image, share the Docker socket via the dind service, and use the CI variables CI_APPLICATION_REPOSITORY, CI_APPLICATION_TAG, DATABASE_URL, KUBE_NAMESPACE, POSTGRES_USER, POSTGRES_PASSWORD, POSTGRES_DB, and any secret variables for the container registry. Artifacts from build (image tag), test (JUnit), and security jobs are retained, and caches are not defined.
